      "id":"business/nils-pratley-on-finance/2013/jul/11/g4s-serco-allegations-serious-fraud-office",
      "sectionId":"business",
      "sectionName":"Business",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-07-11T20:57:35Z",
      "webTitle":"G4S and Serco face a huge hit to their reputations if SFO proves fraud claims",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/nils-pratley-on-finance/2013/jul/11/g4s-serco-allegations-serious-fraud-office",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/business/nils-pratley-on-finance/2013/jul/11/g4s-serco-allegations-serious-fraud-office",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"27",
        "trailText":"<p>Allegations that G4S and Serco charged to tag dead offenders will harm two firms that rely heavily on UK government contracts</p>",
        "headline":"G4S and Serco face a huge hit to their reputations if SFO proves fraud claims",
        "body":"<p>Chris Grayling, justice secretary, says the state of affairs is \"wholly indefensible and unacceptable\" and he is astonished that <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2013/jul/11/g4s-investigated-overcharging-millions-pounds\" title=\"\">two respected government suppliers \"would seek to charge in this way\"</a>. Is the case a slam-dunk then? Have G4S and Serco knowingly been ripping off taxpayers by charging to tag offenders who are dead or in prison? Was it a scam?</p><p>Grayling is not saying that. He has \"no information to confirm that dishonesty has taken place on the part of either supplier\" and admits that his civil servants didn't act when made aware of potential problems in 2008. It seems the jury is out on who is to blame and why.</p><p>For both companies, an awful lot now hangs on the answers. The immediate hit from repaying \"tens of millions\" of pounds would be lost in the wash since both are valued at £3bn or thereabouts. It's the loss of reputation, and thus the knock-on effect on bidding for government work in future, that matters. In the circumstances, the market's instinctive reaction – 8% off Serco's share price and 5.5% of G4S's more lowly rated stock – inevitably amounts to a best guess in the face of inadequate information.</p><p>Serco is a company built on UK government work, which still accounts for 40% of total revenues. It would not survive in its current form if UK public-sector contracts dried up; and the decision to withdraw from tendering for the next tagging contract is a blow in itself. The risk of corporate meltdown is clearly remote but investors still have to price the risk.</p><p>For G4S, it's one thing after another: a farcical £5.2bn bid for ISS of Denmark in 2011; the <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2013/mar/13/g4s-profits-tumble-olympics-failings\" title=\"\">Olympics debacle</a>; a profits warning; and now the arrival of investigators from the Serious Fraud Office.</p><p>G4S is less dependent than Serco on UK government contracts (about 10% of revenues) but it's hard to understand why it didn't follow its rival in co-operating with a further independent review of tagging practices and thus keeping the SFO out of the picture.</p><p>G4S is clearly confident of its case, which shareholders might regard as reassuring. On the other hand, if the customer feels aggrieved surely the sensible course is to grant its wish on how the affair should be investigated. It's an odd sub-plot to a tale that clearly has much further to run.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/412666299|2013-11-05T11:03:52Z|bb364c66d9d2accb2d906069ace982cd53668698 -->",
