      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/business/2013/oct/24/g4s-uk-ireland-head-resigns",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"32",
        "trailText":"<p>Observers suggest Richard Morris's departure is part of bid to rebuild relationship with  government after tagging controversy</p>",
        "headline":"Head of G4S in UK and Ireland resigns",
        "body":"<p>G4S, the world's biggest securities services firm, has parted company with the head of its UK and Irish operations as it tries to improve its relationship with the government after the botched Olympic contract and inquiries into the electronic tagging of criminals.</p><p>Richard Morris, who had been promoted to run the UK and Irish operations in September 2012 in the fallout after the Olympics scandal, is to be replaced by Eddie Aston, who was recruited in July. Aston was previously chief operating officer, having been recruited from Deutsche Post DHL.</p><p>The company confirmed that Morris had resigned but gave no reason for his departure, which is to take place immediately, after a 10-year career with the troubled security firm.</p><p>With a third boss now in charge of the UK arm in as many years, there was speculation that G4S would be hoping to begin to improve its key, but damaged, relationship with the government, for which it already runs prisons, border controls and work programmes.</p><p>The discovery that G4S and its rival Serco had been charging the government for tagging criminals who were dead, in prison or never tagged in the first place prompted the justice secretary, Chris Grayling, to ask the Serious Fraud Office to investigate both firms earlier this year.</p><p>G4S, which employs 620,000 staff, has said that it could not find any evidence to support some of the claims, which it said had been taken out of proportion, but in August it pulled out of the bidding for new tagging contracts.</p><p>Grayling has said that G4S and Serco have overcharged the government by tens of millions of pounds and the Cabinet Office is now in the process of reviewing 28 government contracts the two companies were involved in, worth £1bn. Nine of them involve G4S. The National Audit Office is also conducting a review.</p><p>Morris did not have a seat on the board of the company, which operates in 125 countries around the world, but was a member of the senior executive team. He had worked in the company's justice arm previously and had taken charge of the UK business after the bad management of the Olympics contract cost £88m.</p><p>Nick Buckles, the group chief executive, initially survived the embarrassment of thousands of troops and police being drafted in to guard the Games but not before admitting it had turned into a \"humiliating shambles\".</p><p>Buckles had also overseen the ill-fated attempt to take over Danish rival ISS the previous year. He eventually left in May this year with a <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/may/21/g4s-nick-buckles-quits\" title=\"\">£1.2m payoff</a>.</p><p>It was a profit warning in May that eventually led to Buckles's departure and his replacement by Ashley Almanza, who had joined only three weeks earlier as chief financial officer from BG. Almanza is now embarking on a turnaround strategy and selling off non-core operations following a £550m fundraising in August, which was announced as the company reported a loss after a £202m profit a year earlier.</p><p>Almanza had warned that the share placing in August was needed to avoid a credit downgrade. He also announced plans to sell off businesses in Colombia, Canada and some US operations.</p><p>Rumours that the private equity group Charterhouse has been mulling a takeover bid for one its operations have lifted the shares in recent days. They fell to 200p earlier this year as the company warned about pressure on its margins but have recovered some lost ground, closing at 253p yesterday. In April they were changing hands at more than 300p.</p><p>G4S was recently linked to a joint £1bn bid with the French group Oberthur Technologies to supply Britain's next wave of banknotes.</p><p>• This article was amended on Friday 25 October. The new chief executive of G4S in the UK and Ireland is Eddie Aston, not Eddie Ashton as we had it. The article also said G4S employs 230,000 staff. In fact the company employs 620,000 people globally.</p><p>The new chief executive of G4S in the UK and Ireland is Eddie Aston, not Eddie Ashton as we had it. The article also said G4S employs 230,000 staff. In fact the company employs 620,000 people globally.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420894492|2013-11-05T11:03:52Z|c6b3e8237931f606510f2e573dfa52a238c8554b -->",
