      "id":"business/2013/nov/03/g4s-fireworks-investors",
      "sectionId":"business",
      "sectionName":"Business",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-11-03T00:06:00Z",
      "webTitle":"G4S boss braced for fireworks as investors say group is too big to handle",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/nov/03/g4s-fireworks-investors",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/business/2013/nov/03/g4s-fireworks-investors",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"46",
        "trailText":"<p>The security group put the Olympics fiasco behind it, only to face further serious allegations. Ashley Almanza now has to fight to keep the firm in one piece</p>",
        "headline":"G4S boss braced for fireworks as investors say group is too big to handle",
        "body":"<p>As Ashley Almanza, boss of security group G4S, rehearses his lines this weekend for his crucial 5 November strategy presentation, several investors are whispering of gunpowder, treason and plot. Almanza is facing the biggest presentation of his life: he will have to spell out why the embattled £6bn group should not bow to activist shareholders and split itself up.</p><p>He knows it could be a make-or-break performance. Shareholders remain divided on the question of whether the group is too big for its own good. G4S manages 650,000 staff around the world – and only two years ago came close to <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2011/nov/01/g4s-iss-takeover-fails\" title=\"\">a £5.2bn merger (with Danish rival ISS)</a> that would have seen it become the world's second largest commercial employer, behind Walmart.</p><p>And if shareholder ferment were not trouble enough, the G4S boss is also facing a series of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/may/24/g4s-contract-sexual-assault-referral-centres\" title=\"\">contract meltdowns</a> and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/oct/28/g4s-run-prison-south-africa-investigation\" title=\"\">rogue employee scandals</a>, and <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/jul/11/g4s-investigated-overcharging-millions-pounds\" title=\"\">investigation by the Serious Fraud Office over electronic tagging</a>.</p><p>Steve Woolf, analyst at Numis Securities, said: \"We believe the emphasis [from Almanza on Tuesday] will be on increasing a culture of best practice throughout the group in order to avoid some of the negative press that surfaces in areas such G4S's UK and overseas prison operations.\"</p><p>The past week alone has seen two damaging incidents as far apart as South Africa and Scotland. First came what G4S said were \"unsubstantiated allegations\" of prisoners at its Mangaung prison in Bloemfontein being subjected to electric shocks or forcibly injected with antipsychotic drugs to sedate them.</p><p>The South African government <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/oct/09/g4s-sacked-south-africa-prison-mangaung\" title=\"\">last month took charge of the prison</a> as strike threats and allegations of mistreatment mounted. \"The contractor has effectively lost control of the facility,\" the department of correctional services concluded – a damning verdict in a market Almanza had months earlier flagged as a bright spot.</p><p>Then, last Tuesday, a G4S security guard was <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-24727644\" title=\"\">given a life sentence at Glasgow high court </a>for bludgeoning a 42-year-old Thai conference delegate to death with a fire extinguisher. During the trial, the jury was told that the guard, Clive Carter, had complained of fatigue due to long working hours. On one occasion, months earlier, he had worked 26 consecutive days, the court heard. G4S says Carter worked a standard shift pattern in the period before the murder, adding that previous periods of more intensive employment related to specific events \"in keeping with the standard work patterns of fellow employees\".</p><p>Among earlier flashpoints around the world, one of the most controversial was the unlawful killing by G4S guards of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2010/oct/14/security-guards-accused-jimmy-mubenga-death\" title=\"\">Angolan deportee Jimmy Mubenga </a>three years ago. The Crown Prosecution Service is still considering whether to bring charges after racist material was found on two of the guards'&nbsp;phones.</p><p>Many more sorry G4S episodes have been <a href=\"http://opendemocracy.net/ourkingdom/collections/g4s-securing-whose-world\" title=\"\">catalogued by investigative journalist Clare Sambrook</a>, who questions whether, given its record, G4S is a fit organisation to run prisons, children's homes and detention centres. Those who defend the company's record point out that more than 90% of its staff work in security operations, where occasional dangerous episodes are inevitable.</p><p>Despite the growing list of tragic events, however, what preoccupies investors is G4S's ability to deliver on contracts, growth and profitability. And there was some shareholder unease last year over the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2012/jul/16/police-forces-olympic-security-g4s\" title=\"\">London Olympics security contract debacle</a>, which saw G4S fail to recruit sufficient staff for the contract.</p><p>But investors do not ditch managers over one failure, however high profile. G4S chairman <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/nils-pratley-on-finance/2012/sep/28/nick-buckles-saved-by-g4s-shareholders\" title=\"\">John Connolly presided over a review of then chief executive Nick Buckles's</a> record and found \"no significant shortcomings\". He dismissed calls for Buckles to resign over the Olympics fiasco as \"media frenzy\".</p><p>The view was shared by Invesco fund manager Neil Woodford, who is by no means always in agreement with the G4S board, but said Buckles had an \"excellent\" track record. \"I don't want to throw all that away,\" he said.</p><p>Until May this year, the group had appeared to many in the City as the best in its class. \"We retain G4S as a top pick,\" wrote Panmure Gordon analysts in March. \"We expect the company to deliver creditable growth with margins more positive than [previously] expected.\" Days earlier, analysts at Cantor Fitzgerald took a similar view: \"G4S remains one of our top picks in the sector. We believe [it] should be trading at a premium to its peers reflecting its track record of growth and more attractive operational and geographical profile.\"</p><p><em>Financial Times</em> City editor Jonathan Guthrie declared: \"Shares steamed past their pre-Olympic peak earlier this month and look affordable... Buckles survived the backlash unscathed, save for suffering a media-friendly haircut, having generated a 180% return for shareholders over the previous seven years.\"</p><p>Buckles himself, meanwhile, was bragging that he would get <a href=\"http://www.google.co.uk/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;ved=0CC4QFjAA&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.g4s.com%2F~%2Fmedia%2FFiles%2FInvestor%2520Relations%2520documents%2FCMD%25202012%2FSection%25201%2520-%2520Strategy.ashx&amp;ei=DctzUvO3Lae40QWMrIHwCw&amp;usg=AFQjCNEH-6-_ijunT9EvN8ETcm82vwQA2Q&amp;sig2=JVgzmszaJDr76aP4qi4uCQ\" title=\"\">G4S's £7.5bn revenues up to £10bn by 2014</a>.</p><p>That picture changed abruptly, however, with <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/may/07/g4s-shares-tumble-profit-margins\" title=\"\">a heavy profits warning in May</a>, when Buckles admitted to significant problems in its cash transport and storage business, particularly in the UK and Ireland. This unit, which generates about a quarter of the group's profits by moving money out to cashpoints and in from retailers and other sales businesses, had been losing ground to competitors. \"A lot of new contracts at the back end of last year have not delivered in terms of profitability,\" he said, promising cost reductions. Profitability on other UK contracts was suffering too, he added.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-421600820'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/8/27/1346086990196/G4S-chief-executive-Nick--010.jpg' alt='G4S chief executive Nick Buckles' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Nick Buckles, former chief executive of G4S. Photograph: David Rose/Rex Features</figcaption></figure><p>This was a shock for all those investors who had loyally backed Buckles though the Olympics shambles. The shares lost 15% of their value overnight and the same again in the next two-and-a-half months. Within two weeks of the warning, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/may/21/g4s-nick-buckles-quits\" title=\"\">Buckles was gone</a> and Almanza – who had joined the company as finance director only that month – was hurriedly appointed to succeed him.</p><p>Since then, the new G4S boss has been dashing from crisis to crisis, finding himself in the firing line from investors and human rights campaigners, as well as facing a meltdown in relations with the UK government.</p><p>In June, the group's <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/jun/06/israel-prison-contracts-g4s-agm\" title=\"\">annual shareholder meeting was besieged by campaign groups</a>. Protesters claimed G4S was putting children as young as 12 in solitary confinement in its prisons. War on Want told the meeting it was \"profoundly concerned with G4S's exposure in Palestine\". On two occasions the meeting was disrupted by flash protests over the Mubenga case.</p><p>A month later, relations with the UK government abruptly broke down over allegations that G4S had been overcharging the ministry of justice on an electronic tagging contract, allegedly continuing to charge the department after returning prisoners to prison. Unhappy with Almanza's approach to the contract dispute, justice secretary Chris Grayling referred the matter to the Serious Fraud Office.</p><p>Meanwhile, as if Almanza did not have enough on his plate, short-sellers began targeting G4S, believing the company's finances were in such a mess that it would be scrambling to raise emergency capital and the shares would be forced down in value. And in August they were proved right.</p><p>Delivering <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/nils-pratley-on-finance/2013/aug/28/g4s-share\" title=\"\">his first interim results as chief executive</a>, Almanza announced that new shares equivalent to 10% of existing equity would be placed with institutions, raising £348m to shore up the balance sheet. In addition, £250m would be found from the disposal of peripheral businesses.</p><p>At about that time, Cevian Capital, a £5bn activist investment fund, emerged as a major G4S shareholder, eventually declaring a 5.1% stake and reportedly harbouring aspirations to increase that to 10%. The influential Stockholm-based fund, run by Christer Gardell – a sometime collaborator with US activist investor Carl Icahn – was soon after linked to speculation in the City that Almanza was coming under pressure to dispose of G4S's troubled cash business.</p><p>Cevian declined to comment on reports that it backed such a disposal, but sources close to the fund insisted the group was not confrontational and \"prefers to be described as an engaged shareholder rather than activist\". This claim is not accepted by all in Sweden, where some newspapers call Gardell \"the butcher\" and \"Sweden's Gordon Gekko\". According to former Social Democrat prime minister Goran Persson, it is companies such as Cevian \"who will destroy the national capitalist structures\".</p><p>A week ago, analysts at HSBC declared: \"Hopes that value can be unlocked through break-ups and a rejuvenated strategy are likely to buoy G4S stock through what is perceived as a rump of difficult trading.\"</p><p>Since then, however, it has emerged that G4S has received an approach for its cash division from Charterhouse Capital. It rejected it in less than a week on the grounds that, first, the price of £1.55bn was too low, and second – and more controversially – the unit was, Almanza made it clear, strategically vital to the group and not for sale.</p><p>It is this second argument that is thought to have set him at loggerheads with activists urging a break-up. He will have to enlarge on this theme on Tuesday, as well as delivering a turnaround plan for the struggling UK and Irish cash businesses, which have recently lost major ATM contracts.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-421600821'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Business/Pix/pictures/2013/6/6/1370542394773/Protesters-demonstrate-in-010.jpg' alt='Protesters demonstrate in front of G4S's AGM, June 2013' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Protesters demonstrate at G4S's AGM. Photograph: Stephanie Bosset/  Stephanie Bosset/Demotix/Corbis</figcaption></figure><p>Some shareholders have already come out in support of Almanza. Threadneedle Investments backed the decision to turn Charterhouse away, saying: \"The rejection is consistent with G4S's strategy to sell underperforming businesses – but cash solutions is not one of them.\"</p><p>Sources close to the company say selling the cash arm would be a costly folly in many markets, and that now would be precisely the wrong time to do it. They note that in periods of low interest rates there is less demand from companies to get their cash to the bank quickly.</p><p>It remains to be seen whether Almanza will carry his audience with him on Tuesday. And whatever the verdict, there are unlikely to be any more sudden boardroom departures. Only last year, the group's chairman, Alf Duch-Pedersen, departed in the wake of the aborted ISS takeover. Since then Almanza has arrived, and he has recruited Himanshu Raja from Misys to replace him as finance director. For now at least, investors can agree G4S needs a spell of management stability rather than another body on the bonfire.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421475788|2013-11-05T11:03:52Z|b4a7de56ca61d22c988c7bc079badb3999aa18ec -->",
