      "id":"business/marketforceslive/2013/sep/27/serco-serious-fraud-office-tagging-contract",
      "sectionId":"business",
      "sectionName":"Business",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-09-27T10:38:07Z",
      "webTitle":"Serco slips after Serious Fraud Office considers investigation into tagging contracts",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/marketforceslive/2013/sep/27/serco-serious-fraud-office-tagging-contract",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/business/marketforceslive/2013/sep/27/serco-serious-fraud-office-tagging-contract",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"35",
        "trailText":"<p>Ministry of Justice passes on information to SFO to consider over electronic monitoring</p>",
        "headline":"Serco slips after Serious Fraud Office considers investigation into tagging contracts",
        "body":"<p>It has not been a particularly good week for outsourcing group <strong>Serco</strong>.</p><p>On Monday the company began life in the mid-cap index after its eviction from the FTSE 100, and now it transpires it may be investigated by the Serious Fraud Office over electronic monitoring contracts. Both Serco and rival G4S have been accused of charging the government for tagging criminals who were either in prison, never tagged at all, or dead.</p><p>The Ministry of Justice has already asked the SFO to consider carrying out an investigation into G4S, and now fraud detectives have confirmed they are considering information provided by the ministry on Serco. Serco said after the market closed on Thursday it believed it had billed in accordance with the terms of the contract, and was co-operating with the ministry. It said it would not tolerate poor practice and would put it right wherever it was found.</p><p>Serco's shares have dropped 8p or nearly 1.5% to 543p as investors had their first chance to react to Thursday night's statements, but analysts said the news was not unexpected. Robin Speakman at Shore Capital, in a hold note, said:</p><blockquote><p>Clearly to our minds, whilst this may be disappointing to investors, it is of little surprise; the SFO being in a much stronger position to review and determine the nature of evidence and actions. Serco are due to present their own internal findings on the contract (and related/ancillary issues) at the end of November. We stress, however, that this is unlikely to coincide with a resolution, in our view. We believe that investigations and the resolution process are likely to stretch into the first quarter of 2014. Meanwhile, Serco remains unable to effectively participate in the UK government contracting market, in our opinion. We remain cautious on the economic and reputational damage being inflicted on Serco - in our view a full resolution remains some months away.</p></blockquote><p>Oriel Securities issued a sell recommendation, saying:</p><blockquote><p>It looks to us as if the ministry statement is no more than confirming that the processes of SFO investigation, ministry audit of Serco and G4S and wider review by the Cabinet Office of all contracts held by Serco and G4S across government is on-going. </p></blockquote><p>Caroline de La Soujeole at Cantor Fitzgerald said the update did not make Serco's position materially worse, but added:</p><blockquote><p>If Serco fails to convince the government that it has mended its way it could be frozen from new government work. The UK public sector currently accounts for around 50% of total group sales. Given the cloud of uncertainty hanging over Serco's UK operations, we have a hold recommendation and target price of 550p.<br /> </p></blockquote><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418450333|2013-11-05T11:03:52Z|f6cec4ac018eb5eed25294eff74c3e15ccd8293a -->",
